\end{table}



\paragraph{Affricates}

The affricates {\it /tʃ/} and  {\it /dʒ/} are  treated as single phonemes. They
can occur in word-initial and word-medial positions, although the voiced
affricate is highly restricted. Notice that while  {\it /kp/} and {\it /gb/} do
contrast with {\it /p/}, {\it /b/} {\it /k/} and {\it /g/},   {\it /ʃ/} and  
{\it /ʒ/}
do not exist in the language.  Table
\ref{tab:affricates} provides (near-) minimal pairs. Also, the sound {\it 
tʃ} is pronounced {\it k} by some members of the oldest generation,
e.g. {\it tʃiir} vs. {\it kiir} `taboo',   {\it tʃimmãã} vs. {\it kimmãã}
`pepper',  {\it tʃɪɛŋɛ̃} vs. {\it kɪɛŋɛ̃} `break', etc.  


